	...Christianity and bad conscience

	Nietzsche’s conception is that punishment was originally an expression of immediate anger and the power to exert force. It then became an exchange convenience whereby essentially economic transactions were guaranteed by the threat of violent retribution for defaulting on promises. That arrangement acquired, over time, an ethical status as a moral good in itself.

	The ultimate expression of this arbitrary, not in itself ‘good’ power to punish, Nietzsche argues, has been formalised in Christianity, which has extended the idea of a commercial debt, subject to settlement by payment or punishment, as inevitable and insoluble for all humans.



Nietzsche has a history of ethics and punishment which is that it was invented to make business transactions work then evolved into Christianity

